00:04:21.910 --> 00:04:24.330
So let me really start
out with a little bit

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:28.790
of context, and, in fact, history.

00:04:28.790 --> 00:04:31.710
Humans have known that there
were planets besides the Earth

00:04:31.710 --> 00:04:34.390
for a very, very long time.

00:04:34.390 --> 00:04:40.100 position:56%
In fact, the ancient Babylonians,
over 4000 years ago, around the turn

00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:44.200
of the second millennium, recorded
observations of Mercury, Venus,

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:46.380
Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn.

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:48.090
So as long as 4000 years ago,

00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:51.870
we've known that there were other
planets in our solar system.

00:04:51.870 --> 00:04:54.830
We only missed 2, Uranus
and Neptune.

00:04:54.830 --> 00:04:56.130
That's pretty amazing.

00:04:56.130 --> 00:04:59.140
So we've known for a very, very
long time, longer than the Greeks,

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:01.350
that there were other
planets out there.

00:05:01.350 --> 00:05:05.750
Nobody knows this, this is like
an obscure fact, by the way.

00:05:05.750 --> 00:05:09.880 position:56%
If we skip forward in time from 4000
years ago to about 400 years ago,

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:13.490
there was a guy that some of you
may have heard of, Giordano Bruno.

00:05:13.490 --> 00:05:15.930
Bruno was a famous
astronomer of his era.

00:05:15.930 --> 00:05:18.470
A very, very well-known, very
well-respected astronomer.

00:05:18.470 --> 00:05:24.030
And in 1584, he laid out a
postulate, and his postulate was,

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:27.210
that if you look at the sky
and see all these stars,

00:05:27.210 --> 00:05:30.970
all of those stars
are suns like our own.

00:05:30.970 --> 00:05:33.240
Around each one of those
suns there could be planets,

00:05:33.240 --> 00:05:35.840
and some of those planets
could be like Earth.

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:41.640
And on those planets, there could
be life forms, something like us.

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:45.460
And, fourth, and most
importantly, from his perspective,

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:47.380
those life forms could have souls.

00:05:47.380 --> 00:05:50.110
Now, that last bit is what
got him burned at the stake,

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:53.870
and I'm going to not talk about
that all because that's theology

00:05:53.870 --> 00:05:55.780
and philosophy, not science.

00:05:55.780 --> 00:05:57.890
But we know that the other 3 parts,

00:05:57.890 --> 00:06:00.100
we know that the first one
is essentially correct.

00:06:00.100 --> 00:06:02.860
While stars are, in
fact, very, very diverse,

00:06:02.860 --> 00:06:05.560
our sun is a star like many others.

00:06:05.560 --> 00:06:08.380
We also know that the second
part, that there are planets

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:11.400
around all those stars, that's
pretty close to true too.

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:15.230
There are lots and lots of
planets around a lot of stars.

00:06:15.230 --> 00:06:19.200 position:56%
As for the third, that maybe there's
life on some of those planets,

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:20.500
we have a little way to go.

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:24.350
And hopefully, within my lifetime,
or my daughter's lifetime,

00:06:24.350 --> 00:06:27.340
we'll actually be able to
talk about the possibility

00:06:27.340 --> 00:06:28.640
of life on other planets.

00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:30.300
And at the end of this talk,
I'll say a little bit more

00:06:30.300 --> 00:06:31.760
about how we might get there.

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:37.350
So let's just jump forward again in
time, to now to about 40 years ago.

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:40.580
I don't know if any of you are
science-fiction fans, I am.

00:06:40.580 --> 00:06:44.980 position:56%
But if you looked at
science-fiction works that were made

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:50.360
in this century, whether it be
in TV, movies, or literature,

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:52.930
the idea that there were
planets around stars, in fact,

00:06:52.930 --> 00:06:56.260
planets around a lot of
stars, is ubiquitous.

00:06:56.260 --> 00:06:59.550
It just assumes to be true.

00:06:59.550 --> 00:07:04.230
Now, at the time of all of these
works, there was no evidence,

00:07:04.230 --> 00:07:08.060
direct or indirect,
of a single exoplanet,

00:07:08.060 --> 00:07:11.050
a single planet around
any other star.

00:07:11.050 --> 00:07:13.280
We had not yet found
any evidence whatsoever.

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:18.040
And yet the human imagination
said, they simply have to be there.

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:20.660
Now, all this changed
in around 1989,

00:07:20.660 --> 00:07:24.110
when someone made the
first measurement

00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:28.020
that showed it was possible
for us to find exoplanets.

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:31.600
And this kicked off the
great exoplanet search.

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:34.170
In fact, this week, ironically,
because we didn't really think

00:07:34.170 --> 00:07:35.860
about this when we
scheduled this talk,

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:38.930
this week marks the twentieth
anniversary of the first discovery

00:07:38.930 --> 00:07:42.270
of an exoplanet around
a main sequence star.

00:07:42.270 --> 00:07:45.960
Since we realized we could do
it, people started looking,

00:07:45.960 --> 00:07:47.260
and things have taken off.

00:07:47.260 --> 00:07:48.820
In fact, you'll notice
in one second,

00:07:48.820 --> 00:07:52.840
I have changed the scale bar,
in 2014, because there were

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:57.270
over 900 planets confirmed
last year alone.

00:07:57.270 --> 00:08:00.010
So to date, we have, and
I have to look at my slide

00:08:00.010 --> 00:08:03.250
because the number keeps
changing, as of Monday,

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:08.420
we had 1892 confirmed exoplanets,
planets around other stars

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:11.160
that we've actually been
able to observe and measure,

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:14.760
mostly indirectly, but we
know that they are there.

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:17.630 position:56%
Now, you'll notice on this slide
I've got all these different colors.

00:08:17.630 --> 00:08:20.030
That's to indicate that there
are a lot of different methods

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:22.180
that people have used
to find exoplanets.

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:24.940
And they all have advantages
and disadvantages.

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:28.430
But the 2 that I want to talk
about most today are the 2

00:08:28.430 --> 00:08:30.670
that have been most successful.

00:08:30.670 --> 00:08:34.130
And also because they have
the most relevance for TESS.

00:08:34.130 --> 00:08:37.140
The first of these is the transit
method itself, and I'll describe

00:08:37.140 --> 00:08:39.140
that method in more
detail in a minute.

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:42.870 position:56%
But all of these, all the objects
that are represented by the red part

00:08:42.870 --> 00:08:45.970
of the bar, are transiting
exoplanets.

00:08:45.970 --> 00:08:50.410
And over half of those
planets are transiting planets.

00:08:50.410 --> 00:08:53.430
And in fact, over 1000 of the
confirmed planets were discovered

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:55.800
with one mission, the Kepler
Mission, which has looked

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:58.120
for transiting exoplanets.

00:08:58.120 --> 00:09:00.390
I'll say more about
Kepler in a bit too.

00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:02.950
The other topic, the other
method I want to say something

00:09:02.950 --> 00:09:04.450 position:56%
about is the radial velocity method.

00:09:04.450 --> 00:09:06.080
Those of the objects in blue.

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:09.530 position:56%
That's the oldest and most venerable
method for finding exoplanets.

00:09:09.530 --> 00:09:13.140
And it has a very important
role in how we follow

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:14.740
up on observations from TESS.

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:17.350
And I'll say more about
that in a minute.

00:09:17.350 --> 00:09:19.880
So what are all these objects?

00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:23.820
I'm a scientist, I like
plotting things, so bear with me.

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:27.080
If you look at the vertical
axis here is the mass

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:29.570
of a planet, in Jupiter masses.

00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:32.020
The horizontal axis is the duration

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:35.000
of that planet's year,
the orbital period.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.710
And what you can see is that
if we plot all of these planets

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:39.730
that have been confirmed so far,

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:42.660
they're really pretty
much all over the place.

00:09:42.660 --> 00:09:44.830
They're largely up in this corner.

00:09:44.830 --> 00:09:46.130
There's not a lot down here.

00:09:46.130 --> 00:09:47.570
But there are even
a handful down here.

00:09:47.570 --> 00:09:49.980
Although those yellow ones
are awfully hard to spot.

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:52.870 position:56%
To give you a little bit of context,

00:09:52.870 --> 00:09:57.460
let me add in our solar
system planets.

00:09:57.460 --> 00:10:00.090
Now, there should be
a couple of things

00:10:00.090 --> 00:10:02.640
that strike you right
away about this.

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.860
The first is that there are
only a handful of exoplanets

00:10:05.860 --> 00:10:10.290
down in this regime where our
own planets lie, in this plot.

00:10:10.290 --> 00:10:13.650
Now, there's 2 lessons
that I take away from that.

00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:15.840
The first is that finding
planets like the ones

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:19.850
in our solar system is
really, really hard.

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:22.930
In fact, it is easier to find
planets the bigger they are,

00:10:22.930 --> 00:10:25.190
pretty much no matter
what method you are using.

00:10:25.190 --> 00:10:28.690
Which means we're bias towards
finding things up in here.

00:10:28.690 --> 00:10:31.760
It is also, for the
most successful methods,

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:35.260
easier to find planets the closer
they are to their host star.

00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:37.420
So things in here.

00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:40.530
So it's no surprise, the first
planets we found were all

00:10:40.530 --> 00:10:41.830
up in this range.

00:10:41.830 --> 00:10:44.830 position:56%
And as we've gotten better, as we've
gotten better at the techniques

00:10:44.830 --> 00:10:48.770
and we've explored new techniques,
we've pushed that boundary down,

00:10:48.770 --> 00:10:52.320 position:56%
until now we're starting to just
now see some of the planets that are

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:54.860
like those in our own solar system.

00:10:54.860 --> 00:10:58.100
The second thing I want to
take away from this is, to me,

00:10:58.100 --> 00:10:59.930
actually more interesting.

00:10:59.930 --> 00:11:02.690
And that's that while there
aren't a lot of planets like those

00:11:02.690 --> 00:11:06.290
in our solar system, but gosh
there are a lot of planets here.

00:11:06.290 --> 00:11:09.800
So while our solar system
planets are down here,

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:11.600
we don't have anything
like these objects.

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:13.410
These are completely new.

00:11:13.410 --> 00:11:14.900
These are things that we never saw

00:11:14.900 --> 00:11:17.380
until we started looking
for exoplanets.

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:20.510
And for theorists, this
has been a big problem.

00:11:20.510 --> 00:11:22.450
Now, most of us, probably
not the guy

00:11:22.450 --> 00:11:26.040 position:56%
who wrote this particular theory,
but most of us like new observations

00:11:26.040 --> 00:11:28.080
like this because they
overturn theory.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:31.560
They make us say that the theory
is no good, we need a new one.

00:11:31.560 --> 00:11:33.770
And that's always pretty exciting.

00:11:33.770 --> 00:11:38.330 position:56%
We've found a lot of things in this
data that we never expected to find.

00:11:38.330 --> 00:11:41.570
Let me give you a couple
of quick examples.

00:11:41.570 --> 00:11:45.390
There's the hot Jupiters,
also known as roasters.

00:11:45.390 --> 00:11:49.880
These are Jupiter -sized
planets, but they're in orbits

00:11:49.880 --> 00:11:51.180
of less than about 10 days.

00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:54.680
They're closer to their host
star than Mercury is to our sun.

00:11:54.680 --> 00:11:56.010
They're boiling hot.

00:11:56.010 --> 00:12:00.210
In some cases, they're so
hot that you can see evidence

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:02.800
that there are comet-like
tails, as the atmosphere

00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:06.870
of the planet is being boiled off
and blown away by its host star.

00:12:06.870 --> 00:12:09.050
Again, if you talked to
a theorist 25 years ago,

00:12:09.050 --> 00:12:10.870
and you told him this
object existed,

00:12:10.870 --> 00:12:12.170
they would tell you you were nuts.

00:12:12.170 --> 00:12:14.270
It makes no sense, it
shouldn't be there.

00:12:14.270 --> 00:12:15.920
And yet now we know that they are.

00:12:15.920 --> 00:12:21.190
And theory has evolved to
explain why we actually see them.

00:12:21.190 --> 00:12:23.740
Another class of objects we
didn't expect were what we call

00:12:23.740 --> 00:12:25.410
the super-Earths.

00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:28.240
Again, if I went back in time,
and I talked to theorists,

00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:30.120
what the one thing they
would've told me is that,

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:32.330
the way that planets
form is that it's easy

00:12:32.330 --> 00:12:35.390
to form a rock about Earth size.

00:12:35.390 --> 00:12:38.750
Once you get beyond Earth size,
if you have enough material,

00:12:38.750 --> 00:12:40.600
you go into sort of a
runaway accretion mode.

00:12:40.600 --> 00:12:43.040
You just grab everything
that's nearby.

00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:46.040
So you race straight
from Earth sized

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:48.650
up to Uranus sized with
nothing in between.

00:12:48.650 --> 00:12:51.250
So if I were to look at a thousand
exoplanets, I'll see a bunch

00:12:51.250 --> 00:12:53.070
down here, and I'll
see a bunch up here,

00:12:53.070 --> 00:12:56.130
and I won't see anything
in that box at all.

00:12:56.130 --> 00:12:59.300
Obviously the theorists
were right -- I mean wrong.

00:12:59.300 --> 00:13:01.880
Because that box is
very well populated

00:13:01.880 --> 00:13:03.370
with lots and lots of planets.

00:13:03.370 --> 00:13:05.780
And these are the super-Earths.

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:08.840
Now, again, we have no examples of
these planets in our solar system,

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:11.230
so we don't actually
know what they're like.

00:13:11.230 --> 00:13:17.280 position:56%
Now, on one end of the large end,
things like a 2 Earth radius planet,

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:20.050
those are probably more
like Uranus than Earth.

00:13:20.050 --> 00:13:22.120
They're probably big icy balls.

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:27.200 position:56%
But on the low end, something that's
say 10% or 20% larger than Earth,

00:13:27.200 --> 00:13:28.840
well, that's probably
a rocky planet.

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:30.310
It might be Earthlike.

00:13:30.310 --> 00:13:32.140
It might even be habitable.

00:13:32.140 --> 00:13:36.240
So that leads me to the
topic of habitability.

00:13:36.240 --> 00:13:39.660
The habitable zone and
the goldilocks zone.

00:13:39.660 --> 00:13:42.650 position:56%
Before I talk about that though, let
me give you a couple of statistics.

00:13:42.650 --> 00:13:46.460
We have found, like I said,
almost 1900 exoplanets.

00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:49.820
And from those studies, we've been
able to draw some very serious

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:54.360
and very important inferences
about the population of exoplanets.

00:13:54.360 --> 00:13:56.250
So, for instance, we know

00:13:56.250 --> 00:14:01.780
that in our galaxy there is
approximately 1 planet per star.

00:14:01.780 --> 00:14:03.790
That's not to say all
stars have planets.

00:14:03.790 --> 00:14:06.360
Some stars like our own have many.

00:14:06.360 --> 00:14:07.720
Some have none.

00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:09.250
But on average, there
are as many planets

00:14:09.250 --> 00:14:11.060
in this galaxy as there are stars.

00:14:11.060 --> 00:14:12.750
That's amazing at just
the sheer number

00:14:12.750 --> 00:14:15.030
of planets that are out there.

00:14:15.030 --> 00:14:17.030
We also know that about 1/6,

00:14:17.030 --> 00:14:22.040
17% of all stars have Earth
sized planets around them.

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:24.520
Again, this is, you know,
shocking, 1/6 of a very,

00:14:24.520 --> 00:14:26.780
very large number is
still a very large number.

00:14:26.780 --> 00:14:28.440 position:56%
That's a lot of Earth-sized planets.

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:30.370
That's a lot of potential.

00:14:30.370 --> 00:14:34.190
And perhaps most interestingly,
22% of stars that are

00:14:34.190 --> 00:14:38.540
like our sun have planets
in their habitable zones.

00:14:38.540 --> 00:14:42.940
These are potential places
where we might find life.

00:14:42.940 --> 00:14:45.630
Now, what do I mean
by habitable zone.

00:14:45.630 --> 00:14:47.280
This also known as
the goldilocks zone,

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:50.530
for reasons that will become
apparent very quickly.

00:14:50.530 --> 00:14:54.940 position:56%
It is the range of distances from a
star where you can have liquid water

00:14:54.940 --> 00:14:56.680
on the surface of the planet.

00:14:56.680 --> 00:15:00.640
If you get too close to the star,
then the water gets too hot,

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:02.430
it boils off, it then evaporates,

00:15:02.430 --> 00:15:04.810
and you're left with
a dry dusty rock.

00:15:04.810 --> 00:15:09.260
No water. Not really a
great place for life.

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:11.480
If it gets too far
away from the star,

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:14.880
then all that water precipitates
out, it freezes, it turns into ice,

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:16.850
and now you have a rocky
ball that's covered

00:15:16.850 --> 00:15:18.720
with a thick layer
of ice on top of it.

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:21.990
Again, not really a
great place for life.

00:15:21.990 --> 00:15:24.350
But if you're not too hot,
and you're not too cold,

00:15:24.350 --> 00:15:29.050
if you're just right, then you
can have all the conditions --

00:15:29.050 --> 00:15:34.750
one of the key conditions
for formation of life.

00:15:34.750 --> 00:15:36.050
Now, you'll note, of course,

00:15:36.050 --> 00:15:37.620
that where that habitable
