00:19:45.290 --> 00:19:47.310
So I've mentioned Kepler
a couple of times now,

00:19:47.310 --> 00:19:50.900
so let me say a few words
about what Kepler is.

00:19:50.900 --> 00:19:54.020
Kepler was a mission, or is a
mission, it's now the K2 mission,

00:19:54.020 --> 00:19:58.480
looking for exoplanets by looking
for transits, much like TESS.

00:19:58.480 --> 00:20:02.040
So why do we need TESS, what's
the difference between the two?

00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:07.230
Well, the difference at its core
is largely a philosophical one.

00:20:07.230 --> 00:20:10.360
Kepler was about finding
lots of exoplanets.

00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:12.180
It was about statistics.

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:15.770
Ultimately, the goal was to measure
a quantity that we call eta-Earth,

00:20:15.770 --> 00:20:18.650
which is the frequency
of Earth surround stars,

00:20:18.650 --> 00:20:23.700 position:56%
how common are Earth-sized planets
around all of the stars that we see.

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:27.770
It was not designed to get
detailed characteristics

00:20:27.770 --> 00:20:29.270
of all these exoplanets.

00:20:29.270 --> 00:20:31.340
It was just there to do a census.

00:20:31.340 --> 00:20:35.730
It was the mailer that we get
every 10 years, that's all.

00:20:35.730 --> 00:20:38.150
TESS, on the other hand, is
looking around the neighborhood

00:20:38.150 --> 00:20:40.310
to see what things
are actually like.

00:20:40.310 --> 00:20:45.360
It's looking only within a
well, very nearby distance,

00:20:45.360 --> 00:20:49.310
to look for bright nearby stars
that have transit exoplanets.

00:20:49.310 --> 00:20:51.950
It's about finding the planets
that are really well-suited

00:20:51.950 --> 00:20:54.660
for follow-up observations,
for finding those objects

00:20:54.660 --> 00:20:56.310
that we're going to
want to be studying

00:20:56.310 --> 00:21:00.050
for the next 10, 20,
maybe even 30 years.

00:21:00.050 --> 00:21:03.240
Now, this philosophy
is actually very clear,

00:21:03.240 --> 00:21:05.660
if you look at the way the
different surveys are done.

00:21:05.660 --> 00:21:10.940 position:56%
For Kepler, it looked in a
relatively small portion of the sky.

00:21:10.940 --> 00:21:17.080
But it looked out a long, long
way, over about 3000 light-years.

00:21:17.080 --> 00:21:22.350
TESS, by contrast, only looks about
a few hundred light-years away,

00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:27.400
but it covers almost the entire
sky, more than 400 times more area

00:21:27.400 --> 00:21:30.540
of sky thank Kepler covered.

00:21:30.540 --> 00:21:34.220
So it really is focused on trying
to find those exoplanets that are

00:21:34.220 --> 00:21:36.400
around bright nearby stars.

00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:38.860
Now, you're going to hear me
say bright nearby stars a lot,

00:21:38.860 --> 00:21:41.150
because it's really important.

00:21:41.150 --> 00:21:43.450
How does TESS do this?

00:21:43.450 --> 00:21:45.320
Let's go to the second
part of the name.

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:50.510
The transiting exoplanet survey
satellite, the survey part of TESS.

00:21:50.510 --> 00:21:53.670
Tess has 4 cameras, each
one of which has a 24

00:21:53.670 --> 00:21:55.560
by 24 degree field of view.

00:21:55.560 --> 00:22:00.800
So at any one time, it's looking
at a 24 by 96 degree patch of sky.

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:04.030
This is a really big field of view.

00:22:04.030 --> 00:22:06.820
And in that field of view,
it's looking at a whole bunch

00:22:06.820 --> 00:22:10.660
of individual targets
with small sets of data,

00:22:10.660 --> 00:22:14.000
to try to find those
transiting events.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:17.040
Each one of those observing
sectors is observed for 27 days.

00:22:17.040 --> 00:22:18.660
And over the course of the year,

00:22:18.660 --> 00:22:21.580
we tile 13 of those
observing sectors together

00:22:21.580 --> 00:22:24.210
to cover almost the
entirety of one hemisphere.

00:22:24.210 --> 00:22:28.180
Then we flip around and we repeat
that, and do the same thing

00:22:28.180 --> 00:22:29.490
for the other hemisphere.

00:22:29.490 --> 00:22:33.280
So at the end of 2 years,
we've covered the entire sky

00:22:33.280 --> 00:22:35.810
with a coverage map that
looks something like this.

00:22:35.810 --> 00:22:38.130
So you can see that most of
the sky has been observed

00:22:38.130 --> 00:22:40.150
for at least 27 days.

00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:44.470
And where those observing sectors
overlap, or those tiles intersect,

00:22:44.470 --> 00:22:46.600 position:56%
you get much longer observing times.

00:22:46.600 --> 00:22:49.350
And in fact, up here, at the polls,

00:22:49.350 --> 00:22:52.940
you get almost 1 full
year of time coverage.

00:22:52.940 --> 00:22:54.950
That's really important
because it's at the polls

00:22:54.950 --> 00:22:58.400
that that longer time coverage
that you're able to find planets

00:22:58.400 --> 00:23:00.980
with longer periods, and
you're actually more sensitive

00:23:00.980 --> 00:23:02.690
to small planets.

00:23:02.690 --> 00:23:06.390
So this leads me to this question
