00:25:00.670 --> 00:25:02.900
Why is this so important?

00:25:02.900 --> 00:25:06.180
Well, one of the things that we've
learned from all the exoplanets

00:25:06.180 --> 00:25:10.150 position:56%
that have been done so far, and this
is a really exciting field didn't

00:25:10.150 --> 00:25:12.140
exist 20 years ago, but now it is

00:25:12.140 --> 00:25:16.830 position:56%
like perhaps the single most vibrant
part of the astronomical community.

00:25:16.830 --> 00:25:21.670
One of the things we've learned
is that there's a lot more planets

00:25:21.670 --> 00:25:25.580
out there than we expected, and
that they're very different.

00:25:25.580 --> 00:25:27.690
They're not homogenous bodies.

00:25:27.690 --> 00:25:31.710
They're not Earths and
Venuses and Mars and Jupiters.

00:25:31.710 --> 00:25:34.390
There's planets that are sort of
like this and sort of like this

00:25:34.390 --> 00:25:37.290
and like this, but
