00:25:41.550 --> 00:25:44.850
actually making measurements of
other planets that are out there,

00:25:44.850 --> 00:25:48.430
exoplanets, and say, these 2
planets look similar in some ways

00:25:48.430 --> 00:25:51.440
but they're different in other
ways, can we understand why.

00:25:51.440 --> 00:25:53.920
Can we start to understand
how planets turn

00:25:53.920 --> 00:25:55.590
into the objects that they are.

00:25:55.590 --> 00:25:59.810 position:56%
And to do that we need to actually
do the characterization measurements

00:25:59.810 --> 00:26:04.960
to actually measure the properties
of individual exoplanets.

00:26:04.960 --> 00:26:07.520
Now, this all starts with
the TESS data itself.

00:26:07.520 --> 00:26:10.250
You learn 2 important
things just from looking

00:26:10.250 --> 00:26:12.740
at the transit data
that TESS acquires.

00:26:12.740 --> 00:26:15.800
The first thing you learn
is how big the planet is.

00:26:15.800 --> 00:26:20.850
This may be kind of obvious to
some of you, but just in case.

00:26:20.850 --> 00:26:26.100
The size of that dip in
brightness is determined entirely

00:26:26.100 --> 00:26:29.230
by how big the planet
is relative to the star.

00:26:29.230 --> 00:26:34.670 position:56%
So if you have Jupiter transiting in
front of our sun, Jupiter will block

00:26:34.670 --> 00:26:39.050
about 1% of the light from the sun.

00:26:39.050 --> 00:26:43.660
If, by contrast, I have
Earth orbiting the sun,

00:26:43.660 --> 00:26:49.190
Earth is this little dot right
there, it only blocks about 1/100

00:26:49.190 --> 00:26:52.560
of 1% of light from the sun.

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:58.330 position:56%
So, you know, that dip in brightness
is just the ratio of the area,

00:26:58.330 --> 00:27:02.550
projected area, of the planet
to the area of the star.

00:27:02.550 --> 00:27:05.510
Pretty easy, straightforward.

00:27:05.510 --> 00:27:09.630
You can also note that you can get
the orbital period of a planet,

00:27:09.630 --> 00:27:11.280
you can tell how long a year is.

00:27:11.280 --> 00:27:13.470
If I'm looking at the
Earth transiting the sun,

00:27:13.470 --> 00:27:19.470
then that transit event will occur
exactly every 365 and 1/4 days.

00:27:19.470 --> 00:27:20.870
And I would go low and behold,

00:27:20.870 --> 00:27:25.040
that planet has a year
that's 365 and 1/4 days long.

00:27:25.040 --> 00:27:28.680
Furthermore, if I look carefully
at how long this transit lasts

00:27:28.680 --> 00:27:33.710
and that the shape of the entry
and exit from that transit event,

00:27:33.710 --> 00:27:37.180
I can start talking about things
like the eccentricity of the orbit,

00:27:37.180 --> 00:27:39.270
the inclination angle of the orbit,

00:27:39.270 --> 00:27:41.050
and a number of other
parameters as well.

00:27:41.050 --> 00:27:45.130
I can learn a lot about
the orbital parameters

00:27:45.130 --> 00:27:48.570
of a planet just from
the transit data.

00:27:48.570 --> 00:27:54.020
Unfortunately, this
is really not enough.

00:27:54.020 --> 00:27:56.900
If I were to take a bunch
of planets, as I have done,

00:27:56.900 --> 00:28:00.980
and plot their radius on one axes,
