00:28:27.100 --> 00:28:31.650
They are the how big a planet
would be if it had this mass

00:28:31.650 --> 00:28:34.000
and was made out of this material.

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:36.190
This is kind of obvious, right.

00:28:36.190 --> 00:28:39.890
If I have a bowling
ball and a soccer ball,

00:28:39.890 --> 00:28:43.720
they have the same radius, but the
bowling ball weighs a lot more.

00:28:43.720 --> 00:28:46.550
If I have a shock put and a bowling
ball, they weigh about the same,

00:28:46.550 --> 00:28:49.180
but the shock put's a
lot smaller in radius.

00:28:49.180 --> 00:28:51.160
The same thing is true for planets.

00:28:51.160 --> 00:28:53.750
If I just measure the
radius of a planet,

00:28:53.750 --> 00:28:57.530
and let's say measure something
here at 2 Earth radii, well,

00:28:57.530 --> 00:28:59.950
all those of those things are
about 2 Earth radii and they vary

00:28:59.950 --> 00:29:03.120
from water-like planets to rocky
planets to planets that are heavier

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:05.830
and may even be iron-like.

00:29:05.830 --> 00:29:09.810
Vice versa, if I just had a
mass measurement, then, well,

00:29:09.810 --> 00:29:12.410
I've got something here that looks
heavier than iron, that's weird.

00:29:12.410 --> 00:29:15.750
I've got several things that are
rocky, and one thing that's watery,

00:29:15.750 --> 00:29:18.650
and then some things that are
kind of lying above that curve.

00:29:18.650 --> 00:29:22.150
So if I have just radius,
it's not enough.

00:29:22.150 --> 00:29:25.800 position:56%
If I had just mass, it's not enough.

00:29:25.800 --> 00:29:28.610
Both of those things
give me some idea of what

00:29:28.610 --> 00:29:32.360
that planet might be like, but they
don't really tell me nearly enough

00:29:32.360 --> 00:29:34.540
to start understanding
what it really is like.

00:29:34.540 --> 00:29:35.840
I need both.

00:29:35.840 --> 00:29:37.180
If I have both, I have a density

00:29:37.180 --> 00:29:40.040
and I can tell you what the gross
composition of that planet is.

00:29:40.040 --> 00:29:42.930
I can tell you whether it's a
lump of rock, a big bowl of ice

00:29:42.930 --> 00:29:46.550
and water, a gas giant,
or maybe something bizarre

00:29:46.550 --> 00:29:50.440
like an enormous chunk of
iron in the middle of nowhere.

00:29:50.440 --> 00:29:52.200
So how do I get that
second measurement?

00:29:52.200 --> 00:29:54.340
With the transit data,
I've gotten the radius.

00:29:54.340 --> 00:29:56.250
Now I want to get the mass.

00:29:56.250 --> 00:30:00.270
So this brings me to the
radial velocity technique.

00:30:00.270 --> 00:30:04.340 position:56%
The radial velocity technique is
actually the oldest technique having

00:30:04.340 --> 00:30:06.980
been used for finding exoplanets.

00:30:06.980 --> 00:30:09.090
And it works like this.

00:30:09.090 --> 00:30:12.820
If I look at the light from a star
and I break that into the spectrum,

00:30:12.820 --> 00:30:15.650
into very, very small
chunks of light,

00:30:15.650 --> 00:30:17.460
then what I see are a whole bunch

00:30:17.460 --> 00:30:22.990
of very narrow absorption
bands, absorption lines, even.

00:30:22.990 --> 00:30:26.300
If I watch those lines carefully,

00:30:26.300 --> 00:30:28.590
then I can learn a
lot about the star.

00:30:28.590 --> 00:30:31.240
If that star has a
planet orbiting it,

00:30:31.240 --> 00:30:33.370
then the planet doesn't
just orbit the star,

00:30:33.370 --> 00:30:35.350
the star orbits the planet as well.

00:30:35.350 --> 00:30:38.840
In fact, they both orbit the
center of mass of the system.

00:30:38.840 --> 00:30:42.340
So for every orbit
this planet makes,

00:30:42.340 --> 00:30:45.570
the star is doing a
tiny little pirouette.

00:30:45.570 --> 00:30:48.760
So if you're watching that
spectrum, then what you will see is

00:30:48.760 --> 00:30:52.140
that as the star comes
towards you in that pirouette,

00:30:52.140 --> 00:30:55.240
the lines all shift a little bit
bluer, they get a little bit bluer

00:30:55.240 --> 00:30:58.030
than they would be otherwise,
from the Doppler effect.

00:30:58.030 --> 00:30:59.750
As the star goes away from you,

00:30:59.750 --> 00:31:02.340
they get a little bit redder
from the Doppler effect.

00:31:02.340 --> 00:31:06.020
So over time, I see these
lines doing this, moving back

00:31:06.020 --> 00:31:08.620
and forth, and back and forth.

00:31:08.620 --> 00:31:11.870
And if I measure the frequency
at which they go back and forth,

00:31:11.870 --> 00:31:13.750
I now know the orbital period,

00:31:13.750 --> 00:31:16.940
I know how long the
year is for that planet.

00:31:16.940 --> 00:31:20.400
If I also measure the amplitude,
how far those things move,

00:31:20.400 --> 00:31:23.300
I can tell you how
massive that planet is.

00:31:23.300 --> 00:31:25.740
So if I have that measurement,
in combination

00:31:25.740 --> 00:31:28.770
with the transit measurement, I can
tell you what that planet is made

00:31:28.770 --> 00:31:31.360
out of, roughly speaking.

00:31:31.360 --> 00:31:35.380
So this means that
follow-up observations

00:31:35.380 --> 00:31:38.000
of the TESS targets are going
to be really, really critical.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:41.430
And in fact, part of the TESS
program is to have people

00:31:41.430 --> 00:31:44.130
with ground-based telescopes
following up on these targets,

00:31:44.130 --> 00:31:48.230
to try to make the
measurements to get the masses.

00:31:48.230 --> 00:31:51.160
This is not an easy
measurement to make.

00:31:51.160 --> 00:31:53.930
And well, in fact, it's
extremely challenging.

00:31:53.930 --> 00:31:55.370
So let me give you an example.

00:31:55.370 --> 00:31:58.320
Kepler, with all those planets
that go out very, very far away,

00:31:58.320 --> 00:31:59.980
while it has been responsible
for the detection

00:31:59.980 --> 00:32:03.800
of over 1000 exoplanets,
1000 confirmed exoplanets,

00:32:03.800 --> 00:32:07.710
there almost 4700 additional
exoplanet candidates

00:32:07.710 --> 00:32:10.930
that Kepler has found that
have not yet been confirmed.

00:32:10.930 --> 00:32:12.810
And for many of those,
they haven't been confirmed

00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:16.500
because those stars are down here.

00:32:16.500 --> 00:32:18.500
They are simply too
faint for us to make

00:32:18.500 --> 00:32:23.570
that radial velocity measurement
in order to measure the mass.

00:32:23.570 --> 00:32:24.870
So what would you like?

00:32:24.870 --> 00:32:27.490
You'd like planets
around brighter stars,

00:32:27.490 --> 00:32:30.700
maybe bright nearby stars, in fact.

00:32:30.700 --> 00:32:33.600
And you see, that with TESS,
of course, the stars are about,

00:32:33.600 --> 00:32:37.080
on average, 100 times
brighter than those for Kepler.

00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:40.730
So for Kepler to get a mass of
some of these planets down in here,

00:32:40.730 --> 00:32:46.210
I need weeks or months or many
months of telescope time in order

00:32:46.210 --> 00:32:48.130
to make that measurement.

00:32:48.130 --> 00:32:52.160
With Kepler -- I'm sorry,
with TESS, it will take hours.

00:32:52.160 --> 00:32:55.740
And in fact, some of these stars
are visible to the naked eye.

00:32:55.740 --> 00:32:58.160
An amateur astronomer,
somebody with 4 inch telescope,

00:32:58.160 --> 00:33:01.190 position:56%
could go in their backyard and if
they have a decent camera behind it,

00:33:01.190 --> 00:33:04.220 position:56%
could actually measure that transit.

00:33:04.220 --> 00:33:07.830
Maybe not from DC, it's
too hazy and polluted.

00:33:07.830 --> 00:33:10.150 position:56%
But they go out to West Virginia
somewhere and make that measurement.

00:33:10.150 --> 00:33:12.510
I think that's amazing.

00:33:12.510 --> 00:33:17.010 position:56%
So a big key difference between
Kepler and TESS is that with Kepler,

00:33:17.010 --> 00:33:19.500
you find a new exoplanet
candidate, and you go,

00:33:19.500 --> 00:33:21.110
can we make that follow-up
measurement?

00:33:21.110 --> 00:33:22.990
Is it even possible?

00:33:22.990 --> 00:33:24.360
With TESS, it's going to be,

00:33:24.360 --> 00:33:27.750 position:56%
we've got all these exoplanet
candidates, which one do we do next?

00:33:27.750 --> 00:33:32.810
It's a problem of prioritization,
not one of possibility.

00:33:32.810 --> 00:33:37.120
So as I mentioned before, TESS
actually has partners lined

00:33:37.120 --> 00:33:39.510
up to make a bunch of
these measurements.

00:33:39.510 --> 00:33:41.340
The Las Cumbres Observatory --

00:33:41.340 --> 00:33:46.430 position:56%
actually it's the Las Cumbres Global
Observatory Telescope, I believe.

00:33:46.430 --> 00:33:50.990
Pardon, if any of you speak French,
I'm about to do something horrible.

00:33:50.990 --> 00:33:53.300
The Observatory Haute-Provence.

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:55.630
My friend's pronunciation,
I keep being told is awful.

00:33:55.630 --> 00:33:59.540
And the HARPS Instrument, which is
the high accuracy radial velocity

00:33:59.540 --> 00:34:01.340
planetary search project.

00:34:01.340 --> 00:34:04.880
So these are all partners who
are going to be helping us

00:34:04.880 --> 00:34:06.490
in doing that follow-up work.

00:34:06.490 --> 00:34:08.130
And there's a lot of
other partners here,

00:34:08.130 --> 00:34:13.090
there's just not enough
room to put them on a slide.

00:34:13.090 --> 00:34:15.340
Unfortunately, even once
we have that measurement,

00:34:15.340 --> 00:34:18.090
we still don't really know
that much about the planets.

00:34:18.090 --> 00:34:22.590
Now we know roughly what -- we can
tell it's a rock, that's about it.

00:34:22.590 --> 00:34:24.030
Venus and Earth are both rocks.

00:34:24.030 --> 00:34:26.120
They have about the same mass.

00:34:26.120 --> 00:34:28.080
They have about the same radius.

00:34:28.080 --> 00:34:31.270
They're both in the
habitable zone of the sun.

00:34:31.270 --> 00:34:36.270 position:56%
And yet, it's a gorgeous day outside
here in Washington, DC, on Earth.

00:34:36.270 --> 00:34:39.110
There is no place on Venus where
we can stand on the surface

00:34:39.110 --> 00:34:43.240
and be alive for more
than about a millisecond.

00:34:43.240 --> 00:34:45.640
I like it here, I'm
not going to go there.

00:34:45.640 --> 00:34:49.020
We were talking outside about would
I go to Mars, the answer is maybe.

00:34:49.020 --> 00:34:51.690
I wouldn't go to Venus.

00:34:51.690 --> 00:34:55.090
But if I just had the mass and
radius, they look the same.

00:34:55.090 --> 00:34:56.530
I'd like to be able to
tell the difference.

00:34:56.530 --> 00:34:58.760
I'd like to know which planets
out there are Earthlike,

00:34:58.760 --> 00:35:01.100
which ones are Venous like,
which ones are Mars like.

00:35:01.100 --> 00:35:02.400
How do I do that?

00:35:02.400 --> 00:35:04.840
Well, you need yet
another measurement.

00:35:04.840 --> 00:35:08.350
What you really want
to see is the spectrum

00:35:08.350 --> 00:35:10.500
of the atmosphere of the planet.

00:35:10.500 --> 00:35:13.590
Now, for Earth, this is
this lime and green here.

00:35:13.590 --> 00:35:16.270 position:56%
You see all these big deep features.

00:35:16.270 --> 00:35:18.270
Those are almost all due to water.

00:35:18.270 --> 00:35:19.600
Some of them are due
to carbon dioxide,

00:35:19.600 --> 00:35:21.850
but they're almost
mostly due to water.

00:35:21.850 --> 00:35:23.940
And that's a very good sign.

00:35:23.940 --> 00:35:26.150
We like water on planets.

00:35:26.150 --> 00:35:29.210
Mars, by contrast, here in blue,
really doesn't have many features

00:35:29.210 --> 00:35:32.600
at all because it's
atmosphere is thin and tenuous

00:35:32.600 --> 00:35:35.080
and doesn't have much in it.

00:35:35.080 --> 00:35:38.400
Venus has a lot of features,
but they are not water features.

00:35:38.400 --> 00:35:42.730
They are things like carbon
dioxide and sulfur-based chemicals.

00:35:42.730 --> 00:35:44.390
It's a very different atmosphere,

00:35:44.390 --> 00:35:46.170
so its spectrum is
very, very different.

00:35:46.170 --> 00:35:48.890
If I had a spectrum of
an exoplanet like this,

00:35:48.890 --> 00:35:52.920
I could tell you immediately if it
was one of -- like one of these 3,

00:35:52.920 --> 00:35:54.810
or if it was something
completely different,

00:35:54.810 --> 00:35:57.160
which I really think is likely.

00:35:57.160 --> 00:36:00.240 position:56%
So how do you make that measurement?

00:36:00.240 --> 00:36:01.900
Now we're getting really
into the weeds,

00:36:01.900 --> 00:36:04.190
now things get really hard to do.

00:36:04.190 --> 00:36:06.780
We do that with a technique
we call transfer spectroscopy.

00:36:06.780 --> 00:36:10.450
Now, so imagine for a moment
that you've got a planet.

00:36:10.450 --> 00:36:12.870
And let's imagine that this
planet has an atmosphere,

00:36:12.870 --> 00:36:18.230
a big thick atmosphere, and that
atmosphere absorbs all green light.

00:36:18.230 --> 00:36:19.560 position:56%
All red light goes right through it.

00:36:19.560 --> 00:36:21.050
All blue light goes
right through it.

00:36:21.050 --> 00:36:24.240
But all green light gets completely
absorbed by the atmosphere.

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:27.900
Then if I look at that planet,
and I watch the transit occur

00:36:27.900 --> 00:36:32.730
in red light, what I see
is that just the rock.

00:36:32.730 --> 00:36:34.350
I just see the rock
passing from the star.

00:36:34.350 --> 00:36:35.650
I see the transit.

00:36:35.650 --> 00:36:36.950
Everything is great.

00:36:36.950 --> 00:36:39.270
If I look in blue light,
I see the same thing.

00:36:39.270 --> 00:36:41.390
But if I look in green light,

00:36:41.390 --> 00:36:45.060
suddenly the atmosphere is
absorbing light from the star too,

00:36:45.060 --> 00:36:47.180
so now the planet doesn't
look like it's the rock,

00:36:47.180 --> 00:36:48.930
it looks like it's a bigger rock,

00:36:48.930 --> 00:36:52.530
because the atmosphere is also
blocking out light from the star.

00:36:52.530 --> 00:36:54.540
So when I observe that transit,

00:36:54.540 --> 00:36:57.900 position:56%
I see that the transit starts a
little earlier, ends a little later,

00:36:57.900 --> 00:37:00.560
and it's a little bit deeper.

00:37:00.560 --> 00:37:02.920
If I do this at a lot of
different wavelengths,

00:37:02.920 --> 00:37:05.850
then what I'm measuring is the
apparent size of the planet

00:37:05.850 --> 00:37:08.480
as a function of wavelength.

00:37:08.480 --> 00:37:10.840
That tells me what's
in the atmosphere.

00:37:10.840 --> 00:37:13.720 position:56%
That is a spectrum of the atmosphere

00:37:13.720 --> 00:37:16.100
and tells me what its
composition is.

00:37:16.100 --> 00:37:20.500
Now, this is a very, very, very
challenging measurement to make.

00:37:20.500 --> 00:37:22.620
Remember, I talked about it before,

00:37:22.620 --> 00:37:24.920
a transit measurement
itself is hard,

00:37:24.920 --> 00:37:26.850
because you're measuring
the difference.

00:37:26.850 --> 00:37:28.510
You're measuring this
change in brightness

00:37:28.510 --> 00:37:31.040
of something that's
already pretty faint.

00:37:31.040 --> 00:37:35.050
To do transit spectroscopy, you're
trying to measure the change

00:37:35.050 --> 00:37:38.740
in the change of something
that's already pretty faint.

00:37:38.740 --> 00:37:41.920
So this is an extremely
challenging measurement to make.

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:44.410
And if you want to be
able to make it, you need,

00:37:44.410 --> 00:37:47.250
let me guess, bright nearby stars.

00:37:47.250 --> 00:37:51.040
In fact, you want really
bright stars.

00:37:51.040 --> 00:37:53.770
You want stars that you could
see through a pair of binoculars,

00:37:53.770 --> 00:37:56.110
if not brighter than that.

00:37:56.110 --> 00:37:59.930
These are all the exoplanets
that are currently known,

00:37:59.930 --> 00:38:08.630
as of last night, around very
bright stars, and which transit,

00:38:08.630 --> 00:38:10.900
and there are 30 of them.

00:38:10.900 --> 00:38:13.770
Most of them, of course, are up
here, they're the giant planets.

00:38:13.770 --> 00:38:16.310
In fact, they're the roasters.

00:38:16.310 --> 00:38:19.590
But there are a few down in here.

00:38:19.590 --> 00:38:24.040
Unfortunately, those are all --
there, A, only a handful of them.

00:38:24.040 --> 00:38:28.230
And, B, when I say that they are
bright, they're right at the cutoff

00:38:28.230 --> 00:38:30.960
of what I consider bright enough.

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:32.790
They're not really bright.

00:38:32.790 --> 00:38:34.600
TESS changes that.

00:38:34.600 --> 00:38:38.150
With TESS, suddenly we have
hundreds of these planets

00:38:38.150 --> 00:38:39.540
that are bright enough
for us to make

00:38:39.540 --> 00:38:41.490
that transit spectroscopy
measurement.

00:38:41.490 --> 00:38:43.690
Hundreds of planets where
we will be able to go

00:38:43.690 --> 00:38:46.200
and actually tell you
what the atmosphere

00:38:46.200 --> 00:38:48.380
of that plan is made out of.

00:38:48.380 --> 00:38:53.570 position:56%
And in fact, with future facilities,
like the James Webb space telescope,

00:38:53.570 --> 00:38:56.020
which should launch in about 2018,

00:38:56.020 --> 00:38:58.420
and with future ground-based
telescopes, they are people working

00:38:58.420 --> 00:39:00.610
on 20 and 30 meter
ground-based telescopes,

00:39:00.610 --> 00:39:03.410
that eventually will
actually get built.

00:39:03.410 --> 00:39:05.710
With facilities like those,
we'll actually be able

00:39:05.710 --> 00:39:08.770
to measure the atmospheres
of planets in this range,

00:39:08.770 --> 00:39:10.920
all of these we'll be able to do,
but we'll also be able to do some

00:39:10.920 --> 00:39:12.390
of these small ones as well.

00:39:12.390 --> 00:39:14.120
We won't get down to
the Earth-sized planets.

00:39:14.120 --> 00:39:16.570
That's going to take
something even more powerful

00:39:16.570 --> 00:39:18.630
than what's in the drawing boards.

00:39:18.630 --> 00:39:21.620
But we will be able to do
these super-Earth planets.

00:39:21.620 --> 00:39:25.630
And we may well find some actual
signs of habitable worlds.

00:39:25.630 --> 00:39:27.980
And that's really, really exciting.

00:39:27.980 --> 00:39:32.110
Now, ultimately, we
want to do better

00:39:32.110 --> 00:39:34.120
than even these transit
spectroscopy.

00:39:34.120 --> 00:39:37.520
Ultimately, we would like to
actually observe a planet directly

00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:41.150
and see a spectrum
that looks like this.

00:39:41.150 --> 00:39:44.450
We would like to see a really high
quality spectrum directly measure

00:39:44.450 --> 00:39:45.860
the planet.

00:39:45.860 --> 00:39:48.450
This is actually the
spectrum of the Earth,

00:39:48.450 --> 00:39:50.940
as measured reflected off the moon.

00:39:50.940 --> 00:39:53.390
A very elegant little experiment.

00:39:53.390 --> 00:39:55.310
And you can see in this spectrum,

00:39:55.310 --> 00:39:57.360
there's a lot of stuff
going on in our atmosphere.

00:39:57.360 --> 00:39:59.570
Our atmosphere is very complex.

00:39:59.570 --> 00:40:04.400 position:56%
But there's a couple of key features
that are, to me, as an astronomer,

00:40:04.400 --> 00:40:06.300
really interesting, and
there are things, to me,

00:40:06.300 --> 00:40:08.180
that individually indicate

00:40:08.180 --> 00:40:12.110
that there might be a
nice place for people.

00:40:12.110 --> 00:40:15.760
I see Rayleigh scattering, which
tells me that there's a blue sky.

00:40:15.760 --> 00:40:18.140
I see very strong oxygen features.

00:40:18.140 --> 00:40:20.060
Well, where's the oxygen come from?

00:40:20.060 --> 00:40:22.390
It comes from a lot of places,
but when they're this strong,

00:40:22.390 --> 00:40:25.360
there's something on that
planet that's producing oxygen.

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:27.610
In our case, it's plant life.

00:40:27.610 --> 00:40:30.680
Okay, it's not definitive, but
there's a strong indication here

00:40:30.680 --> 00:40:33.920
that there might be plant
life on this planet.

00:40:33.920 --> 00:40:35.220
Then I see water features.

00:40:35.220 --> 00:40:36.570
I see a lot of water features.

00:40:36.570 --> 00:40:42.650 position:56%
That tells me that water is not only
present but abundant on this planet.

00:40:42.650 --> 00:40:45.140
That there might even be
big bodies of liquid water

00:40:45.140 --> 00:40:47.110
on the surface of this planet.

00:40:47.110 --> 00:40:51.000
Again, this is one of the things
that we consider critical,

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:54.770
necessary for the formation
of life as we know it.

00:40:54.770 --> 00:40:57.160
Then we also see my
favorite feature,

00:40:57.160 --> 00:40:59.430
the methane feature, out here.

00:40:59.430 --> 00:41:06.480 position:56%
On Earth, methane is almost entirely
produced by biological life.

00:41:06.480 --> 00:41:12.110
Whether it is bacteria on
the ground or in jungles,

00:41:12.110 --> 00:41:14.860
breaking down organic matter,
or flatulent livestock,

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:16.160
almost all of the methane

00:41:16.160 --> 00:41:19.660
in our atmosphere is actually
produced by biological life.

00:41:19.660 --> 00:41:22.880
So if we saw the combination of all
of these features in the spectrum

00:41:22.880 --> 00:41:28.510
of an exoplanet, we would have,
not a definitive, but a very, very,

00:41:28.510 --> 00:41:33.490 position:56%
very strong case that that planet
is habitable and maybe even habited.

00:41:33.490 --> 00:41:36.910
Again, we're not going to be
able to make that measurement

00:41:36.910 --> 00:41:39.980 position:56%
in the near future, that's something
that will happen down the line.

00:41:39.980 --> 00:41:42.690
And maybe it will be a target
that's been found by TESS.

00:41:42.690 --> 00:41:45.570
I think it is likely that the first
time we see a spectrum like that,

00:41:45.570 --> 00:41:48.420
it will be something
that TESS finds.

00:41:48.420 --> 00:41:50.270
But that spectrum will have to wait

00:41:50.270 --> 00:41:52.340
for the next generation
of space telescopes.

00:41:52.340 --> 00:41:56.930
Which brings me to my final
actual slide, which is to point

00:41:56.930 --> 00:42:00.810
out that TESS is part
of a long line.

00:42:00.810 --> 00:42:03.210
Exoplanets is a new
field, as I said before,

00:42:03.210 --> 00:42:05.160 position:56%
it's really only about 20 years old.

00:42:05.160 --> 00:42:07.080
And it's really only
been in the past 10 years

00:42:07.080 --> 00:42:10.140
that it's really taken
off in a powerful way.

00:42:10.140 --> 00:42:12.420
And it's built on the
legacy of a lot

00:42:12.420 --> 00:42:14.700
of other facilities and missions.

00:42:14.700 --> 00:42:17.050
It started with ground-based
observatories.

00:42:17.050 --> 00:42:19.870
But then the Hubble space telescope
has made great discoveries.

00:42:19.870 --> 00:42:22.370
Spitzer has been used
to study exoplanets.

00:42:22.370 --> 00:42:25.710 position:56%
And the Kepler mission that I
talked about is responsible for more

00:42:25.710 --> 00:42:29.400
than half the exoplanets that we
know about, that we've confirmed.

00:42:29.400 --> 00:42:31.100
TESS is the next logical step.

00:42:31.100 --> 00:42:34.540
Because we're no longer interested
in just finding exoplanets,

00:42:34.540 --> 00:42:36.340
we're interested now
in finding exoplanets

00:42:36.340 --> 00:42:37.900
that we can actually study.

00:42:37.900 --> 00:42:41.700
We're actually interested in
learning what exoplanets are like.

00:42:41.700 --> 00:42:44.480
And this is a very big
departure, this is a new direction,

00:42:44.480 --> 00:42:49.460
this is opening the door
for comparative planetology.

00:42:49.460 --> 00:42:52.530
Beyond TESS, JWST is going
to be a critical facility

00:42:52.530 --> 00:42:54.090
for following up these objects.

00:42:54.090 --> 00:42:59.620
We're going to have the target list
that exoplanet scientists are going

00:42:59.620 --> 00:43:01.620
to be using for the next 20 years.

00:43:01.620 --> 00:43:05.340
And JWST is going to be the
best way to study those objects

00:43:05.340 --> 00:43:08.560
over the next decade
or maybe longer.

00:43:08.560 --> 00:43:11.140
Beyond that, the WFirst
NASA mission, which is going

00:43:11.140 --> 00:43:14.710
to launch sometime in the next
decade, I think it's 2023,

00:43:14.710 --> 00:43:19.030
but please don't quote me on that.

00:43:19.030 --> 00:43:21.310
That is going to also be
used to study exoplanets.

00:43:21.310 --> 00:43:25.170
And beyond that, astronomers
are looking at possible missions

00:43:25.170 --> 00:43:26.470
in the long-term, something

00:43:26.470 --> 00:43:28.860
like what's shown here is
the New World telescope,

00:43:28.860 --> 00:43:33.010
even larger telescopes that are
optimized solely for the purpose

00:43:33.010 --> 00:43:35.560
of getting a spectrum
of an exoplanet,

00:43:35.560 --> 00:43:39.470
something that looks like that.

00:43:39.470 --> 00:43:44.370
And ultimately, maybe before I die,

00:43:44.370 --> 00:43:48.100
we will actually have not just
a whole range of exoplanets,

00:43:48.100 --> 00:43:51.380
but we'll have a wide
variety of exo-Earths.

00:43:51.380 --> 00:43:53.540
We will be able to
talk about the fact

00:43:53.540 --> 00:43:58.810 position:56%
that our Earth is a unique object,
but there are other Earth's similar,

00:43:58.810 --> 00:44:00.550
similar enough that
they could support life.

00:44:00.550 --> 00:44:03.120
And we can start understanding
the differences between planets

00:44:03.120 --> 00:44:06.680
that are habitable, not just
the differences between planets.

