00:46:39.020 --> 00:46:42.570
So the question is,
what about giant stars?

00:46:42.570 --> 00:46:48.890
Do we see smaller stars eclipsing
or transiting other larger stars?

00:46:48.890 --> 00:46:54.490
Do we see -- okay, I think
that's about it, right?

00:46:54.490 --> 00:46:55.880
The short answer is yes.

00:46:55.880 --> 00:46:59.250
In fact, we find a lot of what
we call eclipsing binaries.

00:46:59.250 --> 00:47:03.250 position:56%
And in many cases, those are 2
stars that are around the same size,

00:47:03.250 --> 00:47:05.120
that can be very different in size.

00:47:05.120 --> 00:47:08.060
But, in fact, one of the
biggest sources of noise

00:47:08.060 --> 00:47:10.210
that we've got are
eclipsing binaries.

00:47:10.210 --> 00:47:14.460
Because if you have a big star and
a little star, it produces a signal

00:47:14.460 --> 00:47:17.020
that looks a lot like
a transiting exoplanet.

00:47:17.020 --> 00:47:19.690
You know, if you look
at it in more detail,

00:47:19.690 --> 00:47:25.060
you realize that's not a planet,
but it takes some extra work.

00:47:25.060 --> 00:47:31.220
Now, as for giant stars, typically
we don't observe giant stars

00:47:31.220 --> 00:47:33.060
on purpose.

00:47:33.060 --> 00:47:36.780
The reason for that is that, if I
have a planet around a giant star,

00:47:36.780 --> 00:47:41.220 position:56%
remember, that signal, that drop in
brightness, is the ratio of the area

00:47:41.220 --> 00:47:42.970
of the planet to the
area of the star.

00:47:42.970 --> 00:47:47.810
If the area of the star is this,
then my signal drops like a rock,

00:47:47.810 --> 00:47:50.320
and now I've got no
depth to measure,

00:47:50.320 --> 00:47:53.360
because it's so small
it's not miserable.

00:47:53.360 --> 00:47:56.860
So we don't on purpose
look at giant stars.

00:47:56.860 --> 00:48:00.640
Now, for TESS, this ancillary
data, when I mentioned briefly,

00:48:00.640 --> 00:48:02.480
is we're going to be getting
these full frame images.

00:48:02.480 --> 00:48:05.800
We're going to be taking pictures
of the entire observation sector,

00:48:05.800 --> 00:48:10.200
that entire 24 by 96 degree
field of view, every 30 minutes.

00:48:10.200 --> 00:48:16.310
And anything that's in that data,
