00:49:09.230 --> 00:49:12.220
I also commented that some stars
have no planets around them.

00:49:12.220 --> 00:49:14.770
Do we know that for a fact?

00:49:14.770 --> 00:49:19.820
And no, it's hard to
know that for a fact.

00:49:19.820 --> 00:49:26.180
If a star has a planet in
a very, very distant orbit,

00:49:26.180 --> 00:49:28.520
it would be very difficult
to detect the methods

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:31.870
that are really effective,
like transfer rate of velocity.

00:49:33.510 --> 00:49:38.040
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:49:38.040 --> 00:49:39.720
What we can say is that there
are some stars out there

00:49:39.720 --> 00:49:45.130
that don't have any planets
within a certain distance,

00:49:45.130 --> 00:49:48.970
but that's about it.

00:49:48.970 --> 00:49:54.620
And there's other stars where we
can make theoretical arguments

00:49:54.620 --> 00:49:56.060
that there shouldn't
be any planets, right.

00:49:56.060 --> 00:49:59.690
If I see a supergiant, a star
that has just recently gone

00:49:59.690 --> 00:50:01.910
into the supergiant phase,
if it had any planets,

00:50:01.910 --> 00:50:04.970
they should've been
sucked up and eaten.

00:50:04.970 --> 00:50:06.690
They shouldn't be there.

00:50:06.690 --> 00:50:08.790
But I don't know for a fact
that there aren't any there.

00:50:08.790 --> 00:50:11.360
One of the limitations of both
the rate of velocity technique

00:50:11.360 --> 00:50:15.020
and the transit technique is that
it requires a given orientation.

00:50:15.020 --> 00:50:17.920 position:56%
If I have, you know, if it's
orbiting this way, then it transits,

00:50:17.920 --> 00:50:20.600
the planet passes in
front of the sun.

00:50:20.600 --> 00:50:23.510
But if the orbit is
inclined this way,

00:50:23.510 --> 00:50:25.870
it never transits,
there is no transit.

00:50:25.870 --> 00:50:28.680
Likewise, the radial
velocity measurement,

00:50:28.680 --> 00:50:32.350
if it's aligned this way,
then that star is moving back

00:50:32.350 --> 00:50:34.540
and forth relative to
your line of sight.

00:50:34.540 --> 00:50:38.440 position:56%
But if that orbit is inclined this
direction, then it's moving this way

00:50:38.440 --> 00:50:40.450
in your line of sight, and
you get no Doppler effect,

00:50:40.450 --> 00:50:42.310
so you can't see it.

00:50:42.310 --> 00:50:45.890
So there's a lot of limitations,

00:50:45.890 --> 00:50:47.950
but it's essentially
a statistical argument

00:50:47.950 --> 00:50:53.460
that what we're seeing is
consistent with these numbers.

00:50:53.460 --> 00:50:55.130
If the number were
significantly higher,

00:50:55.130 --> 00:50:56.780 position:56%
we would expect to find more things.

00:50:56.780 --> 00:51:01.930
But if there's some unexpected
unknown population of planets

00:51:01.930 --> 00:51:08.350
out at 10 times Pluto's distance,
that we've never seen before, well,

00:51:08.350 --> 00:51:10.970
we can't count those because
they shouldn't be there

00:51:10.970 --> 00:51:14.900
and we haven't seen them.

